textDelta: why do countries protect their own companies in international trade There are a few reasons countries might protect their own companies in international trade. One reason is that the country might want to ensure that its companies have a fair chance to compete in the global marketplace. Additionally, the country might want to ensure that its companies are able to generate revenue and jobs within the country. Finally, the country might believe that its companies are more likely to behave ethically than foreign companies.

moscow treaty on strategic offensive reductions states The Moscow Treaty on Strategic Offensive Reductions (SORT) was a treaty between the United States of America and the Russian Federation on the Reduction and Limitation of Strategic Offensive Arms. Signed on May 24, 2002, it was the first treaty to reduce nuclear weapons since the START I treaty in 1991. The treaty required both countries to reduce their strategic nuclear arsenals to 1,700–2,200 warheads by 2012.
